passages.text: Australia | Telecom Services
Equity ResearchAugust 28,2025

Mobile subs net adds are moderating after the July price increases. Felix has been leading the mobile momentum to date, the only problem is Felix is about half the price of postpaid plans, and even lower as Felix is running a promotion. Fixed Broadband is at risk from the upcoming NBN Speed Boost.Positively, FCF is improving and gearing is at comfortable levels.

**1H25 result.** Proforma EBITDA of $786m (post the asset sales to Vocus) is in line with our forecast. It represents 48% of the guided FY EBITDA at the midpoint of $1,605-1,655m,consistent with the prior year.

**Moderating mobile momentum.** 1H mobile netadds were split postpaid +15k, digital-first brands (prepaid) +55k and traditional prepaid +30k. Post the price increases in July, TPG is expecting the momentum to moderate in 2H, with a similar mix to 1H. The strength in digital-first brands is primarily led by Felix, which has been marketed heavily by TPG. Given its digital delivery model, Felix can be easily rolled out to regional areas without having a physical presence, and its % margins are better than traditional prepaid, and possibly postpaid.However, its dollar margin is likely to be much lower given it is about half the price of postpaid plans. TPG is also introducing promotions on Felix (50% off for 3m) and has not raised its prices since 2023. It shows that TPG has been attracting price-conscious consumers.

**Fixed broadband still challenging.** Total subscribers declined -55k in the half, an acceleration from prior periods. Fixed Wireless (+17k) could only partially offset the significant decline (-73k) in NBN. Several challenger brands have emerged offering NBN 500 Mbps plans, therefore, the upcoming Speed Boost could be another churn event for TPG. Although Fixed Wireless still has its place in the market, its value proposition may become less compelling as it can only offer up to 100 Mbps.

**Improving FCF and comfortable gearing.** FCF is going to improve significantly in FY25 due to growth in EBITDA, and reductions in interest costs and capex, and the unwind of handset receivables. TPG is still committed to the $100m cost reduction target by FY29 through simplifications of consumer plans and IT applications. At gearing of 1.7x (ex-leases), TPG is well under its bank debt covenant of 3.75x.

**Earnings and valuation** We trimmed our forecasts due to lower mobile subs momentum. The downgrades to our NRNAT are significant, given that TPG is starting to pay cash tax post the sale of assets to VGES.

**Lucy Krimmer * | Equity Associate**

TPG has a lower cost- to- serve than other major telcos in Australia, and that allows it to charge consumers lower prices. But this competitive advantage has been eroded because of the NBN and there is a risk that new entrants can aggressively compete against TPG in the SMB segment.

Post the divestment of fibre assets to Vocus, TPG loses its title as an integrated telecom provider. While we don't mind an asset- light model, TPG needs to rely on providing a great customer experience to grow its market share.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

TPG pays out \(\) 1.61\$ per share from Vocus deal proceeds. DRP sees full uptake and TPG can pay down \(\) 2.4bn\$ in debt. In FY26, TPG can grow postpaid subs by 30k and prepaid subs by 156k. Our PT is A\$5.40 under this scenario and derived from a DCF valuation and SoTP valuation, and accounting for the capital return.
TPG is able to gain more market share in mobile by taking share from Optus and Telstra, particularly in regional areas following the MOCN deal. Our PT is A\$5.90, derived from a DCF valuation.
Price war in Mobile. Network disruptions occur during the process and there is a need to increase capex. Our PT is A\$4.60, derived from a DCF valuation.

All of TPG's radio access equipment was purchased from Huawei, banned in Australia since 2018. TPG is replacing all its Huawei equipment. The merger with VHA has reduced the stake of David Teoh (Exec Chairman) to \(14\%\) so he has less influence now than pre- merger.

1) TPG will power Australia operations with \(100\%\) renewable electricity by 2025. 
2) Female representation \(14\%\) in leadership; \(35\%\) across the workforce; \(20\%\) in STEM functions; and \(30\%\) female directors. 
3) Community investment of at least \(\) 1\$ mn per annum.
1) What are you investing in to protect TPG and your customers' data?
2) TPG is a major telco in Australia with high pricing power. How will the business ensure that price rises will be fair for customers as the economic landscape seems to be deteriorating?
3) TPG is still majority-owned by JV Co (Vodafone and Hutchison). How do you protect the interest of minority shareholders?
ESG Sector Deep Dive: Telco and Media
The result was largely pre- reported earlier in the month when TPG provided its capital management plans post the divestment of its Fibre assets, read here.

1H25 proforma EBITDA of \(\) 786m\(post the fibre sale to Vocus) was consistent with our forecast. It represents 48% of the full - year guidance for\) \ \(1,605 - 1,655m\) at the midpoint. The 1H/2H split is consistent with FY24. Comparison of the result with consensus estimates can be cumbersome given that some estimates are actuals, as opposed to proforma, and some estimates were stale.

There is still no pricing for the dividend re- investment plan, including how the discount will be calculated and applied, but it will be designed to incentivise participation. Management noted there is the option for the plan to be underwritten, however do not think it will be necessary.
Mobile subs net adds momentum from 1H25 continued into July. TPG also mentioned that price increases pushed through in July (at Vodafone only) may affect growth rates in 2H, with similar mix to 1H.

- EBITDA of \(\) 1,605-1,655m\(. The midpoint implies a 2% increase vs FY24 PF. Capital Expenditure:\) \ \(790m\) in FY25. There will be a lower capex target range from FY27 of \(\) 550-650m\$

- Postpaid mobile net adds were \(+15k\) to 2.86 million for the Jun-25 half, which was strong vs TLS \(+4k\) and Optus \(-30k\) for the same period. There was a slowdown across the broader market, but TPG was able to take share following the expansion of its network post the TPG-Optus MOCN deal.
- Prepaid net adds were solid too, adding 86k to 2.36 million during the half across Vodafone prepaid, TPG, iNet, felix, Lebara and Kogan.com. Wholesale net adds (MVNOs) were -3k in 2H to 110k.
Figure 5 - Postpaid Mobile Plan 1 Pricing
Source: Company data, Jefferies

- 1H25 Mobile postpaid ARPU only increased marginally, adding \(1.8\%\) to \(\) 48.51\(. TPG decided not to implement a price increase at Vodafone during the half (typically passed through in January). There was also discounting during the period -\) \ \(10\) off for new subs, diluting ARPU.

- 1H25 Prepaid ARPU grew \(4.9\%\) to \(\) 20.74\(. There were minimal prepaid price increases in the half, with ARPU growth mostly coming from consumers upgrading their plans within the tier 2 offerings. Overall Mobile ARPU (ex MVNOs) grew \(1.0\%\) to \(\) 34.97\(/month, reflecting moderate price rises.\)

- During the year, NBN subscribers declined \(73k\) to \(1.611\) million, reflecting ongoing market competition from both telco and non-telco operators, partially mitigated by TPG promotional activity following the relaunch of the new TPG consumer brand in April 2025. NBN ARPU increased \(1.3\%\) to \(\) 68.5\(/month.\)
- Fixed wireless subs grew \(17k\) to \(285k\) , despite stronger competition. Fixed Wireless ARPU increased \(11.9\%\) to \(\) 49.1\(/month.\)

TPG Telecom is an Australian telecommunications and IT company servicing residential, business, government and wholesale customers. The company offers ADSL2+, NBN, Fibre Optic and Ethernet broadband access, telephony services, Internet Protocol Television, SIM Only Mobile plans and other business networking solutions. TPG was founded in 1992 and has become the second- largest broadband provider in Australia.

We value TPG using a mix of DCF and SOTP Methodology, and also account for the capital return using the net proceeds from the Vocus deal. Our DCF assumptions are WACC of \(8.6\%\) , risk- free rate \(4.5\%\) and equity risk premium \(5.0\%\) . We assume a beta of 1.10 and terminal growth rate of \(2.0\%\) . We have added the PV of tax losses in our DCF. For the SOTP valuation, we have assumed \(7.5x\) FY26 EBITDA for the mobile business, and \(4.5x\) for the Consumer fixed division.

Upside risks: TPG could get a large number of subscriber net adds post the MOCN deal, further traction in fixed wireless, price increases. Downside risks: no solution for regional mobile coverage, increased competition especially in the low- cost segment.

We value TLS using a DCF and SOTP methodology (average). For the DCF, we have used a WACC of \(7.7\%\) and beta of 1.0. We have assumed a risk- free rate of \(4.5\%\) , market risk premium of \(5.0\%\) , and terminal growth rate of \(2.5\%\) . For the breakup valuation, we assume FY26E multiples of Amplitel 18x EBITDA, InfraCo Fixed 16x, Mobile 7.5x, NAS 6x, Fixed Consumer 4x, Fixed Wholesale 4x, Data & Connectivity 7x, International Ex- Digicel 6.5x, and Digicel 6.0x. Risks: increased competition in fixed enterprise and consumer markets, and higher inflation on opex and capex.
